article.description: Dee Davis scored 18 points, including seven in overtime, to spark Vanderbilt (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) to a 66-59 victory over No. 18 Georgia in a Southeastern Conference matchup.
article.headline: Earley forces overtime
article.linkText: Davis sparks Vanderbilt to OT win over Georgia
article.story:
ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Dee Davis scored eight of her game-high 18
points in overtime to lead Vanderbilt (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) to a 66-59 win over
No. 18 Georgia on Sunday and third place in the Southeastern
Conference.

	   Vanderbilt's Ashley Earley forced overtime when she picked up a
loose ball and hit a jumper from the right baseline as the horn
sounded to tie the game at 54.

	   In overtime, Earley opened the scoring with a jumper in the lane
to give the Commodores the lead for good. Janese Hardrick heaved a
shot at the final buzzer, the only basket the Lady Dogs managed in
the extra period.

	   Carla Thomas scored 17 points for Vanderbilt (21-6, 10-4 SEC)
and Early added 14 points and 15 rebounds.

	   Sherill Baker led Georgia (21-8, 9-5 SEC) with 13 points, and
freshman Tasha Humphrey had 11 points and 10 rebounds. Cori
Chambers and Hardrick scored 10 apiece.

	   A 3-pointer by Chambers with 1:50 to play put Georgia ahead
54-48, but turnovers helped Vanderbilt climb back into the game.
After Davis hit a followup with 1:07 to play in regulation, closing
the gap to 54-50, Georgia's Rebecca Rowsey stepped backcourt
against the Commordore press, leading to another Earley score.

	   Then Hardrick traveled against the press, setting up Earley's
shot to the tie the game at the end of regulation.

	   The first half was a defensive struggle, surprising since
Vanderbilt entered the game ranked second in the nation in scoring
and Georgia ranked 15th.

	   The Lady Dogs led 20-18 on two free throws by Sherill Baker with
3:43 to go in the half, but Vanderbilt scored the last seven points
of the half. Vanderbilt led 25-20 at the break as Georgia shot just
23 percent from the field.
